[!INFO] Is an autoimmume, T cell infiltrative disease.
#2021BSQ-NOV Q32

  • Autoimmunity -> TSH-Receptor antibodies (thyrotropin receptor or TRAb) stimulate thyroid gland to make thyroid hormones. -> diffuse, non tender, goiter. (MCQ Point: TSH receptor inhibiting antibodies are also formed)
  • Histology: Diffuse, hyperplasia and hypertrophy; follicular cells become tall and columnar with crowding and formation of papillae with no neovascularization. T cell infiltrates are present within thyroid.
  • Graves eye disease is a prominent feature. Occurs because of T cell infiltrations;
    • Volume of retro-orbital tissue is increased by 1) T cell infiltration, 2) Inflammatory oedema, 3) Increased extracellular matrix deposition, 4) increased adipocytes.
  • Orbitopathy and pretibial myxoedema are not related to thyroxine levels. Pretibial myxoedema is caused by deposition of glycosaminoglycans and T cell infiltration.

[!INFO] Other causes of Acute Flaccid paralysis
[[2021-Basic Sciences#Selected causes of acute flaccid paralysis]]

  1. Acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (AIDP) - commonest, motor predominant with sensory involvement

Critical to distinguish AML from chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) in blast crisis because CML in blast crysis can be treated with [[2021-Basic Sciences#Tyrosine kinases|tyrosine kinase inhibitors.]]

[!TIP] Only organisms containing V in their name have LIVER stages.

Plasmodium falciparum invades human erythrocytes by redundant pathways.

In P Ovale, all stages of the life cycle are seen in the blood film whereas in P. falciparum only trophozoites and gametocytes are seen in the blood. (therefore, if all forms are seen, chloroquine can be given. )

Pathogenesis of disease in malaria infection

All species of plasmodium adhere to cell surfaces in humans. In P falciparum, the time of adhesion is a significant portion of the life cycle.

Falciparum infection of RBC -> RBC produces sticky knobs of proteins -> RBC adhere to capillary endothelim -> sequestration -> partial blood flow obstruction -> compliactions like cerebral malaria and renal failure.

Thick and thin films are used for rapid diagnosis. Thick Vs. Thin film preparation

  • Metabolic -> Hypoglycaemia is a feature of severe disease / metabolic acidosis

    Quinine based regiments can be used as alternatives if ACT resistance is prevalent. Consists of quinine + (doxycycline / tetracyclin / clindamycin). ACT is preferred over quinine regiments because quinine regimens can cause reversible tinitus and high tone hearing loss + GI side effects.

[!INFO] Summary

  • Uncomplicated non falciparum malaria
    • Treatment is directed at the erythrocytic forms.
    • If species unknown of patient develops severe malaria -> treat as for falciparum.
    • If chloroquine sensitive, give chloroquine or ACT.
    • If chloroquine resistant, give ACT.
    • Fever and parasitaemia stellet in 2 - 4 days.
    • Antirelapse therapy with primaquine is started when symptoms begin to resolve.
  • Treatment of severe malaria:
    • If no ACT resistance, give IV artesunate.
    • If ACT resistance is prevalent (south east asia) -> combine IV quinine with IV ACT.

artesunate is safe in any trimester.

Cervicofascial actinomyocosis

  • Actinomycosis - a bacterial infection.
  • Actinomyces are gram +ve bacterial, facultative anaerobes which can have a filamentous, fungal like appearance. (but filaments are much thinner than fungal filaments)
  • It is a commensal of the oral cavity and tonsillar crypts -> infection typically occurs by direct spread after dental infection or OMF trauma.
  • They are slow growing fastidious organisms requiring 14 to 21 days to grown ins special media.
  • Same family as mycobacteria and nocardia -> infection can be hard to distinguish from them.
  • The most common presentation of actinomycosis is cervicofascial actinomyosis (50%).
  • It presents as a soft tissue swelling on the head / neck.
  • It's a chronic disease characterized by abscess formation, sinus tracts, fistulae and tissue fibrosis.
  • "sulfur granules" are charactericaly visible (although not unique) in infections but they are made of fillament + polysaccharide balls, not sulfur.
  • Treatment: prolonged course of high dose penicillin / amoxicillin or Co-Amoxiclav.

Candidiasis

#2021BSQ-NOV Q39

  • Candida is a normal commensal of the genitourinary and GI tracts.
  • It can cause local infection of the mucosa when the normal microbiota is disrupted.
  • More extensive local infection occurs in deficiencies of cell mediated immunity and in critically ill patients.
  • If candida gains access to the blood stream, systemic infection can occur with pyelonoephritis, endocarditis and meningitis. Devices and anatomic abnormalities also predispose to candidaemia. (i.e in the blood)

Poliomyelitis

Key facts about the polio virus


Neurotropic virus spread by faeco-oral route.
Now endemic only in Pakistan and Afghanistan.
Affects motor neurons in the brain stem and spinal cord.

Clinical presentation:
Vast majority are asymptomatic.
About 5% develop a flu like illness with sore throat and fatigue.
The remainder (1%) develop more severe illness.
The remainder develop

  • non-paralytic polio (fever, meningismus, headache, vomiting)
  • paralytic polio
    • Acute flaccid paralysis with pain due to destruction of anterior horn cells.
    • Can involve a single muscle, group of muscles, quadriparesis or respiratory failure.
    • About 66% of patients never regain full strength.
  • Management is supportive.

Oral polio vaccine

#2021BSQ-NOV Q42
Types of polio vaccine

  • Inactivated vaccine (IPV) - polio virus inactivated with formaldehyde.

    • Given IV
    • Cannot cause vaccine induced polio illness.
    • Countries are phasing out oral polio vaccine in favour of IPV.
    • Fractional doses are given in low income countries to minimize cost. Lower seroconversion rates but it effectively boosts pre existing antibody titres.
    • Does not provide good mucosal immunity when compared with OPV but it can boost immunity previously induced by OPV.

  • Live attenuated oral polio vaccine (OPV)

    • used in developing countries primarily due to low cost.
    • Advantages of OPV
      • Produces good mucosal immunity
      • Reduced risk of transmission to non-immunized people.
      • Initially the world used a trivalent OPV. Now, everyone uses a 2 valent vaccine.
      • The 2 valent vaccine had the vaccine against "type 2" removed because that virus is no longer present in nature and continued use to 3-valent vaccine led to increased incidence of vaccine associated poliomyelitis for that strain.
    • OPV is being phased out in favour if IPV.

Selected causes of acute flaccid paralysis

Source

  1. Spinal cord level
    1. Post infectious transverse myelitis (transverse myelitis isn't always caused by trauma)
    2. [[2022-SBR-MAY#West Nile Virus |West Nile virus]]
    3. Arterial or venous spinal cord infarction
    4. Compression from abscess, tumour or haemorrhage.
  2. Nerve level
    1. Neuropathies: GBS, AMAN, AMSAN,
    2. Mononeuritis multiplex
    3. Acute intermittent porphyria
    4. Toxic neuropathies
  3. Neuromuscular junction
    1. MG
    2. Lamber Eaton syndrome
    3. Botulism
    4. Tick paralysis - caused by neurotoxins in tick saliva. They may prevent release of acetylcholine. Develops after tick as been attached for 3 to 7 days. Treatable if diagnosed quickly. Otherwise, respiratory failure and death. Clinical presentation is similar to GBS. Commonest in North America and Australia.
  4. Muscle level - myopathies
    1. Rhabdomyolysis
    2. Carnitine deficiency
    3. Periodic paralysis
    4. Inflammatory myopathy

Tyrosine kinases


Types of cell signalling mechanisms - Youtube

See Robbins table 2-10.

They are transmembrane cell receptors used in signalling.
They are the most common type of enzyme-coupled receptors (ECP) which in turn are one of 3 types of transmembrane receptors;
- The second type of ECP is tyrosine kinase associated receptors (no intrinsic enzyme activity)
- the third type of ECP is receptor serine / threonine kinases (type 1 and type 2)
Kinase = phosphorylator. I.e They phosphorylate tyrosine residues when stimulated by their signalling molecule.

Source
In step 3, dimerized receptor tyrosine kinsases phosphorylate each other.
The activated relay proteins show are transduse the message to varied intracelluar pathways.
Examples: insulin or growth factor.

Prader - willi syndrome

Prader-Willi syndrome (PWS) is a disorder caused by a deletion or disruption of genes in the proximal arm of chromosome 15.

[!TIP] Mnemonic: Lazy baby
Features : diminished fetal activity, obesity, hypotonia, intellectual disability, short stature, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, strabismus, and small hands and feet.

Diarrhoea due to preformed toxins

#2021BSQ-NOV Q37

Symptoms suggesting diarhoeal illness caused by preformed toxins:

  • Absolutely Rapid onset of symptoms : within hours.
    • Bacteria which start to form toxin after ingestion take time to produce symptoms. (usually> 24 hours)
  • Vomiting predominates in the clinical picture.
  • Pathogens causing diarrhoea this way are
    • Staphylococcus aureas - Toxin is produced on food at room temperature; food doesn't taste or smell odd. Onset as rapid as Source 30 minutes!
    • and Bacillsu cereus

They can easily contaminate food and infection is via ingestion.
They can cause a watery diarrhoea [[2022-November#^5eaea3|watery Diarrhoea]]They can even survive and reproduce at refrigerator temperatures.
Enveloped single stranded RNA virus.

Birds are the reservoir.
Spread to humans by mosquito bite.
It infects neurons of the brain and spinal cord.
